description:
This hippo was curiously determined to investigate this zebra carcass that crocodiles were consuming. At times, it seemed content to "nose" the carcass, at other points, the hippo would attack the crocodiles. Exciting.

See paired observation of the crocodiles for photos of crocs eating zebra: http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/843687
Waterhorses watching wary wildebeest wade a waterway.

The captive offspring of a gift a pair of pygmy hippos from the Liberian president Willian Tubman to the Kenyan president Jomo Kenyatta in the 1970s. News story of the mother's death here: http://www.kws.org/info/news/2011/14_12_2011_pigmyhippo.html
Hippos at the hippo pool near Mpala Research Centre
Seen at the Mzima Springs in the park.
I can not remember exactly where in Kenya I was when these were taken, I will try to narrow down the area
We spotted two hippos one male one female wallowing in a small pool alone.

Several hippos seen in fairly small pool. Observations by Janine Duffy with Tour Leader Martin Maderthaner, Roger Smith, and guests on Explore Nature Safari.  Also seen: Nile Crocodile, and 8 Rock Dassies nearby.  Birds seen submitted to eBird.
It was dead, and had a nasty gash in its armpit. Rigor mortis had clearly set in, and it was also very bloated from the buildup of gas.
In a waterhole of the River Mara. Masai Mara, Kenya. See more in my African Safari album : www.flickr.com/photos/25171569@N02/albums/72157669809103977

I observed this family of hippos below my tent at the Hotel Fairmont Mara Safari Club in the River Mara on the opposite bank of the river. I have many other mammal photos from this trip, however this is one I am certain of the  approximate location for.
Viewed from shore in lake Victoria. Mother plus calf. In an area that conflicts with human use.
The larger hippo in the pictures doesn't have ears - not sure it's caused by birth defect or some early injury

Hippo family got on the "hippo beach" for a nap. It was quite fun to watch their communication (shouting match) for sleeping arrangement - it appears baby hippos lined up to lie down first and then adult hippos got down to baracade the young ones. And soon the hippo's wisdom and caution were proven necessary as a nile crocodile showed up on the beach and ruined the nap!
Saw this hippopotamus from the grounds at the Sopa Lodge.
one of a pair seen trotting through the grass, Suyian side of the river. River was high, strong current. I assume they were moving upstream
2 adults, 2 calves. One calf quite small
